      "web_research": {
        "results": [
          {
            "possibleIdentity": "Jill Rosenberg was an artist and administrative professional active in the New York art scene during the late 1960s and 1970s. She is historically recognized for her association with Experiments in Art and Technology (E.A.T.), a non-profit organization co-founded by Billy Klüver and Robert Rauschenberg to foster collaborations between artists, engineers, and scientists. Rosenberg served in significant administrative roles for E.A.T., including as Executive Secretary and a key contact for the organization's Technical Service Program, where she acted as a liaison between the art and engineering communities. In her own creative practice, she is known for designing the artwork for the UNICEF collector's plate titled 'The Earth is But One Country' (c. 1979), which featured a 'cosmic design' and represented themes of global unity. She was also part of the early 1960s Greenwich Village cultural scene, where she was associated with figures in the folk music and art communities.",
            "sources": [
              "https://www.villagepreservation.org/2015/01/06/folk-music-in-greenwich-village-1961-1970/",
